 in Hartford. Mark Twain was substantially formed during the intervening years, as Clemens came East, gained fame and fortune with the publication of Innocents Abroad, courted and married Olivia Langdon, and established himself as a professional writer. Each of these steps represented a profound change in the former Wild Humorist of the Pacific Slope as he sifted through the elements in his personality and began to assume the qualities we now associate with him. The tale that unfolds here shows how, through that process, the Mark Twain of the late 1860s became the Mark Twain of all time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Americany19th centuryvBiography. 4aAmerica. 4aAmerican literature. 4aEnglish Literature. 4ahistory of literature. 4ahumor. 4aindividual authors. 4aliterature. 4apoetry. 4apoets. 4apresent. 4awriter. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052034823340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520348240?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520348240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520348240/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles